Synthax

The synthax of g2r is heavily inspired by ggplot2.

ggplot2 to g2r synthax map.
ggplot2 g2r
ggplot g2
aes asp
scale_* gauge_*
geom_* fig_*
facet_* plane_*
theme_* motif_*

Aspects

In g2r you use aspects (asp) instead of aesthetics (aes) in ggplot2 but they work in very much the same way.

g2(cars, asp(dist, speed, size = speed)) %>% 
  fig_point()

Then you can use gauges (instead of scales in ggplot2) to manipulate those aspects.

g2(cars, asp(dist, speed, color = speed, size = 10)) %>% 
  fig_point() %>% 
  gauge_color(c("blue", "white", "red"))

It may seem like some some figures (equivalent to geoms) are missing, but technically all are available.

fruits %>% 
  g2(asp(value, color = fruit)) %>% 
  fig_interval_stack() %>% 
  coord_type("theta")

You won’t find fig_bar but fig_interval does the trick. Below we the adjust function which is similar to using the stat argument in ggplot2.

g2(temp, asp(month, temp, color = city)) %>% 
  fig_interval_dodge()

There are no fig_boxplot either, yet.

library(dplyr)
library(purrr)
#> Warning: package 'purrr' was built under R version 3.5.2

df <- rep(100, 8) %>% 
  map(runif) %>% 
  map(boxplot, plot = FALSE) %>% 
  map_dfr(function(x){
    x$stats %>% 
      unlist() %>% 
      t %>% 
      as.data.frame
  }) %>% 
  mutate(
    group = LETTERS[1:n()],
    type = rep(letters[1:2], 4)
  ) %>% 
  tidyr::nest(V1, V2, V3, V4, V5)

df$data <- df$data %>% 
  map(unlist) %>% 
  map(unname)

Plot created data

g2(df, asp(type, data, adjust = "dodge", shape = "box", size = 60, color = group)) %>% 
  fig_schema()

There is a fig_violin but it expects the data in a specific format.

get_density <- function(k = "A"){
  density <- runif(100) %>% 
    density() 
  df <- dplyr::tibble(key = k)
  df$x <- list(density$x)
  df$y <- list(density$y)
  return(df)
}

df <- get_density("A") %>% 
  bind_rows(get_density("B")) %>% 
  bind_rows(get_density("C"))

g2(df, asp(key, x, size = y, color = key)) %>% 
  fig_violin(style(fillOpacity = .3)) %>% 
  conf_tooltip(FALSE)

A heatmap is easier.

library(dplyr)

data("diamonds", package = "ggplot2")

palette <- c("blue", "cyan", "lime", "yellow", "red")

diamonds %>% 
  count(carat, price) %>% 
  g2(asp(carat, price, color = n)) %>% 
  fig_heatmap() %>% 
  gauge_color(palette)
iris %>%
  g2(asp(Petal.Length, Petal.Width, color = Species)) %>% 
  fig_point() %>%
  plane_wrap(planes(Species), type = "tree")

If you navigate the original examples of the g2 JavaScript you will notice that they often make use of the dataset library to transform the data. This is imprelement as the function alter, mainly to easily replicate examples.

aletered_fruits <- fruits %>% 
  mutate(value = value * 100) %>% 
  select(name = fruit, value) %>% 
  alter(type = "waffle", maxCount = 500, rows = 12) 
 
g2(aletered_fruits, asp(x, y, shape = "square", color = name, size = 10)) %>% 
  fig_point(axes = FALSE) %>% 
  gauge_axis(x, FALSE) %>% 
  motif(padding = rep(50, 4))

The alter function is used internally by get_map to process GeoJSON files. It’ll enable you to easily build otherwise difficult charts.

dist <- jsonlite::fromJSON("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/antvis/g2/master/demos/data/gaussion-distribution.json")

bins <- alter(dist, type = "bin.hexagon", fields = list("x", "y"), bins = list(10, 5), sizeByCount = TRUE)

g2(bins, asp(x, y, color = count, opacity = count)) %>% 
  fig_polygon(tooltip = FALSE) %>% 
  gauge_color("#BAE7FF-#1890FF-#0050B3")

Though there is a fig_voronoi helper now.

df <- dplyr::tibble(
  x = runif(25, 1, 500),
  y = runif(25, 1, 500),
  value = runif(25, 1, 500)
) %>% 
  map_df(round)

v <- alter(df, type = "diagram.voronoi", fields = list("x", "y"), size = list(500, 500), as = list("x_", "y_"), .rename = FALSE)

g2(v, asp(x_, y_, color = value)) %>% 
  fig_polygon(tooltip = FALSE) %>% 
  gauge_x_linear(min = 0)
